Current paper introduction: 
The identity of dark matter remains one of the most profound mysteries in modern physics. The standard cosmological model, Lambda Cold Dark Matter ($\Lambda$CDM), successfully describes the large-scale structure of the universe, from the cosmic microwave background to the distribution of galaxy clusters. However, on smaller scales, the simple, non-interacting nature of cold dark matter is less stringently tested, and various theoretical extensions predict new microphysical behaviors. Among the most compelling possibilities is that dark matter particles interact with baryons through a non-gravitational force. Such interactions, if present, would have left a distinct imprint on the primordial density field.

Elastic scattering between dark matter and baryons in the early universe facilitates momentum and heat exchange between the two fluids. This process effectively imparts a pressure on the coupled fluid, counteracting gravitational collapse below a characteristic scale. The primary cosmological consequence is a suppression of the matter power spectrum at small scales, leading to a cutoff in the halo mass function that prevents the formation of the lowest-mass objects. The scale of this suppression is directly tied to the dark matter-baryon scattering cross-section, making the search for a cutoff in the abundance of small halos a powerful method for probing the fundamental properties of dark matter.

The 21 cm forest offers a unique and direct window into this regime. Arising from the absorption of radio waves from distant sources by intervening clouds of neutral hydrogen, the 21 cm forest directly traces the distribution of gas in the high-redshift intergalactic medium and within the very first gravitationally bound objects, known as minihalos. Since these minihalos are the structures most affected by a suppression of small-scale power, the statistics of 21 cm absorption lines are exceptionally sensitive to the presence of dark matter-baryon interactions. A deficit of these absorbers compared to the predictions of $\Lambda$CDM would serve as a clear signature of new physics.

In this paper, we quantify the optimal strategy for detecting the signature of dark matter-baryon scattering with the 21 cm forest. We use a semi-analytic framework to model the statistics of 21 cm absorbers and demonstrate that the suppression of low-mass minihalos imprints a distinct feature on the shape of the optical depth distribution. This feature provides a powerful discriminant, allowing the effects of dark matter microphysics to be distinguished from uncertainties in astrophysical parameters, such as the intensity of the ionizing background. By performing a Fisher forecast that incorporates a realistic evolution for the population of background radio sources, we map the sensitivity of this probe across cosmic time. Our analysis identifies an optimal observational window at redshifts $z \sim 8-10$, where the combination of intrinsic physical sensitivity and statistical power is maximized. This work establishes a clear path forward for using next-generation radio observatories to place leading constraints on the nature of dark matter.

