\subsection{Fisher forecast and the optimal observational window}

While the intrinsic sensitivity to $M_{cut}$ is highest at early times, a realistic observational forecast must also account for the availability of background radio sources. We performed a Fisher matrix forecast for the parameter set $\{M_{cut}, f_{cool}, \bar{x}_{HI}\}$, incorporating a model where the number of available lines of sight, $N_{los}$, decreases at higher redshifts. This creates a fundamental tension: the physical signal is stronger at high redshift, but the statistical power to detect it is weaker due to increased Poisson noise.

Figure \ref{fig:image5} shows the resulting marginalized 1-$\sigma$ uncertainty on the cutoff mass, $\sigma(M_{cut})$. The uncertainty is minimized at $z=7$ ($\sigma(M_{cut}) \approx 1127 \, M_\odot$) and increases steadily with redshift, driven by the diminishing number of background sources. This trend demonstrates that the loss of statistical power at high redshift ultimately outweighs the gain in intrinsic physical sensitivity.

Synthesizing these competing effects, we identify an optimal observational window at $z \sim 8-10$. In this redshift range, the statistical uncertainty on $M_{cut}$ remains low (e.g., $\sigma(M_{cut}) \approx 1907 \, M_\odot$ at $z=10$), while the intrinsic signature is significantly more distinct than at $z=7$. Furthermore, the off-diagonal elements of the Fisher matrix confirm that the shape-based fingerprint of $M_{cut}$ remains highly effective at breaking degeneracies with astrophysical parameters like the mean neutral fraction, $\bar{x}_{HI}$. This window therefore represents a strategic balance between maximizing the intrinsic signal and minimizing statistical uncertainty.

